When the Wheeling and Lake Erie train crew was switching out cars at Hickory siding in Hickory, PA after picking up a set of car from the Markwest facility in Westland, PA, they noticed a petroleum odor coming from car CTCX 736489.  This car had been one of the ones picked up from Westland.  They then set the car out to the siding and called the dispatcher who then in turn called John Vergis, WLE Environmental Officer, to handle the situation.  John called Specialized Professional Services out of nearby Washington, PA to look at the car.  Once they investigated the car they found that the vacuum relief device was leaking vapor.  The O ring was deteriorated.  They removed the vacuum relief device and installed a plug.  An OTMA-3 was submitted by Markwest and the car continued to be offloaded and then to home shop.

column168: Call received from Tower Manager about possible spill and odor on A/C at Gate A11 in DFW Airport at approximately 1650 on 05JAN, 2016.      After arrival at the aircraft it was determined that the affected area was in the forward belly of the A/C and that there was no longer any odor up there and the small amount of liquid had been cleaned up. A/C maintenance had already cleared the A/C of any adverse effects. I was informed that MOD Denny O’Connell and the TSA had taken a few suspect bags to screen them. The TSA subsequently cleared those bags as No Threat but one of the bags had a lot of cologne and other fragrances and some of the clothes in it were wet. This was determined to be the bag that contained the source of the liquid/odor.     Upon examining the bag and looking inside for the actual source, one spray can of Axe had no top and appeared to have been pressed while in the bag. It was determined to have likely been in a state of continual spray, which explained the wet belongings in the bag and the strong, sweet odor.     The clothes and other affected cloth items were hung over a rail to dry (these were never subsequently forwarded due to residual vapor concerns). Other smaller, safe items were put in a small plastic bag and eventually forwarded to final destination. The other potentially unsafe items were disposed of locally. There was also a can of spray suede that is more like an aerosol can of non-latex spray paint with a heavy ether smell that was also not forwarded.
column169: Cap in place on top of commercial product to prevent accidental activation.  Possible redesign of can to prevent accidental activation

A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was in the ten day storage yard of the intermediate truck transfer facility.  When the rear door was opened, it was found that a drum had tipped partially over and leaked a small amount out of the lid which was popped off.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the spilled material from the trailer floor, placed it into the drum and reclosed the lid.  The shipment was then transferred to a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: There were two causes for the spill.  The drum was not secured from movement and had tipped over partially.  The drum was rated for solids but contained liquid.  The origin location was notified, and will contact the generator about proper container selection.  They will also speak with the driver who picked up the shipment and retrain him on proper container selection and speak with all appropriate dock personnel who loaded the trailer without proper blocking and bracing.

column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A LIMITED QUANTITY IN A UN 4G & AN OVERPACK WITH A JERRICAN AS THE OUTER PACKAGING. AS THE SHIPMENT WAS A LIMITED & QUANTITY, COUPLED BY A OVERPACK THERE ARE NO CLOSURE REQUIREMENTS. I'VE NEVER SEEN A JERRICAN AS OUTER SO I OPENED THE BOX. I FOUND NOT A COMBINATION PACKAGE IN SIDE THE OVERPACK. INSTEAD I FOUND A SINGLE OPAQUE JUG THAT WASN'T MARKED OR LABELED AS AN OUTER PACKAGE INSIDE AN OVERPACK MUST BE. I SPOKE TO THE A SHIPPER WHO CONFUSED A COMBINATION PACKAGE WITH AN OVERPACK, WAS CONFUSED AS TO WHAT THE AUSPICES OF LIMITED QUANTITY CONTAINED, BUT WAS CONVINCED THE ONE GALLON PLASTIC JERRICAN WASTED WITH THE BOX. PERHAPS. I NOTIFIED SA KEN HOLMAN WITH THE MEMPHIS SECFO AND THE PACKAGE WAS HELD FOR AN FAA INSPECTION.

column62: Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Commodity Self-Ignition
column168: ON 1/7/2015 AT APPOX 23:30 A PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE ON FIRE WHILE TRAVELING ON A CONVEYOR BELT IN THE UPS SYRACUSE NY HUB. A UPS EMPLOYEE SAW THE FIRE AND RESPONDED WITH A DRY CHEMICAL FIRE EXTINGUISHER EXTINGUISHING THE FLAME. NO OTHER PACKAGES WERE INVOLVED. NO INJURIES OCCURRED. NO EVACUATION WAS ORDER AND THERE WAS NO NEED TO CALL THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. NO OTHER PROPERTY DAMAGE WAS REPORTED. THE PACKAGE CONTAINED 4 8.3 OX AEROSOL HAIRSPRAY BOTTLE ALL WITH CAPS HAVING FALLEN OFF. THE BOTTLES WERE PACKED LOOSELY IN THE BOX ALONG WITH 4 -1 GALLONS CONTAINERS OF LIQUID DISH SOAP. ONE OF THE HAIRSPRAY BOTTLE HAD COMPLETELY DISCHARGED INSIDE THE BOX. ITS BELIEVED THE VAPORS ESCAPING THE PACKAGE WERE IGNITED BY STATIC ELECTRIC ON THE CONVEYOR BELT. THE PACKAGE HAS BEEN SECURED IN A METAL DRUM OUTSIDE OF THE FACILITY

column168: LTCX1922 was discovered by a local Trainmaster at 0645 hours on 18 January 2016 in the CSX Willard Yard, Willard, OH to have what appeared as an excessive amount of ice and condensation on the exterior of the valve operating housing. The trainmaster notified the CSX Hazardous Materials Manager by contacting the Public Safety Coordination Center at 0655 hours.     The Trainmaster confirmed there was no noise emanating from the car, nor was there any amount of vapor being released that was inconsistent with normal venting. As a precaution an emergency response contractor was dispatched to the yard to investigate, and the shipper was notified.     The contractor discovered the liquid line valve to be partially open, and the liquid line valve packing gland nut was insufficiently applied / tight. The valve was closed, packing gland nut was tightened, and the release was secured. The shipper was notified, dispatched a local technician for their documentation, and as of this report is performing a root cause analysis to prevent future occurrences.

column168: UTLX 200851 was noticed by a passing Amtrak train and was leaking fluid down the side of the car. Local fire department arrived and evaluated the car. Liquid was noticed leaking down the side of the car from the base of the liquid valve. FD vented the car via the vapor valve and the leaking subsided.   Belfor Environmental responded and noticed that the leak was from around the threads, below the liquid valve. Belfor was able to turn the liquid valve with a pipe wrench approximately another 1/4 turn. Belfor then removed the liquid valve completely, removed all of the excessive previous sealing material/Teflon tape, reapplied a petroleum specific thread sealant, and reapplied the liquid valve. Belfor reassessed the tank car the following morning with no leaks present.  On 1/13/2016, a verbal OTMA was acquired from FRA HazMat Specialist Kevin Blackwell to move the car the 4 mile distance to the Suncor Energy offloading facility in Durham, CO. The car was confirmed to have been moved and offloaded at the Suncor facility.

column168: The Tradebe Transportation was taking a bulk tanker trailer (i.e., number 103) from East Chicago, Indiana to Greencastle, Indiana.   Tanker 103 contained flammable liquid waste.  While in route the driver was alerted that material from the dome area had leaked on to the side of the tanker.  The driver immediately pulled to the side of Highway 231 in Crawfordsville, Indiana and discovered a minimal amount of waste had splashed on to the side of tank.   The driver immediately placed absorbent materials under the trailer as preventative measures and then contacted the Tradebe Environmental personnel.   Tradebe Environmental personnel contracted a local environmental response contractor to conduct the corrective actions needed.   The contractor advised that they observed two small areas with approximate sizes of five (5) to (7) seven inches in diameter had dripped onto the asphalt roadway.   These areas were abated by the application of Portland cement compound as an absorbent by the contractor.  The contractor also discovered an open ended fitting next to the dome area that was not tight.  The contractor corrected the situation and wiped up some of the free liquid in the Lading System.  The Contractor believes that the extremely cold temperatures caused the lading System drains to freeze which then prevented the liquid from escaping the Lading System.  With the tanker trailer situation corrected, the truck was sent to the facility for off-loading and then directed  to truck wash for final  cleanup of the dried waste material.
column169: Corrective Actions taken is the establishment of a tanker trailer check sheet as well as additional training for prevention of this type of occurrence  are;  · Loading personnel are to double check all seals and valves to confirm that they are secure and tight before allowing the tanker to leave  the work area;  · Anytime the truck stops at a location before arriving at the destination, double check all seals and valves for leakage.  · Document all of the activities that were performed.

column168: A Univar driver picked up 4 totes from Thatcher Chemical on PO#561951. Driver returned to the yard and dropped the trailer for material handlers to unload the next morning. The next morning 1-6-16, the material handler opened trailer 18703 and smelled Bleach or Sodium Hypochlorite. The MH then went to the side of the trailer and noticed that there was something leaking from the nose of the trailer on the ground. The MH immediately notified the BOM and BOS of what he found. Initial inspection revealed that one of the totes was leaking from a defective ball valve. Most of the product that leaked was still on the floor of the trailer other than a 4x4 puddle on the ground. BOM notified tank farm employees and clean up ensued. The material was cleaned up without further incident.
column169: During daily STAR meeting we trained employees on checking ball valves prior to shipment.  WE also asked drivers to be more diligent when picking up totes from vendors and customers.

At approximately 11:30 am CT on January 4, 2016 BNSF train yard inspectors at the BNSF Barstow train yard detected an odor near car UTLX 40849.  Upon further examination the car was found to be leaking from the area of the manway lid.  BNSF hazmat responders investigated and found the vacuum relief valve (VRV) which was affixed to the manway lid to be leaking.  They opened the manway to inspect the underside of the valve and found the sealing o-ring at the base of the valve had rolled out of position.  BNSF hazmat responders removed the VRV and disassembled.  The existing gasket was moved back into its proper place and the valve was re-applied to the car.  While the manway was opened, responders replaced the manway gasket even though there was no evidence of a leak from that location.  During this process the car was in a departing train heading for Bakersfield.  The car departed and arrived Bakersfield, CA without further release.  MP Environmental contractor was called to the car in Bakersfield to remove the repaired VRV and apply a suitable pipe plug in it's place.  Shipper was notified and applied for OTMA-3 from FRA.  Total release was estimated at 3 ounces and was confined to the top of the tank car.  No impact to the environment occurred.
column169: Shipper should initiate a process in their pre-trip inspection to account for the possibility of a failing VRV by applying minimum pressure to detect a leak from any fixture which would include the VRV.

column168: Driver was waiting on a lease rod to offload fuel. Fuel delivery was cancelled. Driver proceeded to leave the area, was met by a inbound pipe truck. Driver had to back down the county road. Snow/blizzard conditions created low visibility. Driver slid off the road down an embankment. Hose reel connection to the tank failed due to the truck rollover. Weavertown Environmental called to the scene to remove any released fuel. Minor fuel amounts reached a nearby waterway. Booms put into place. Area was monitored for the next 6 days. PA DEP inspected and authorized the case closure on 1/28/16.
column169: Due to the weather conditions at the time of the event, two improvement measures have been taken;  1) Better communication via dispatch to the driver so that in the event a load is cancelled, the driver will be notified sooner, and will be able to depart the area before conditions worsen.   2) In the event that a driver needs to back down a roadway due to an oncoming truck, the driver will do the following.  a) Ask the oncoming driver to spot him into a safe pull off location  b) Radio the customer and ask for assistance in spotting the backing vehicle.

column168: Jeremy traylor received a call for a leaking package at revenue recovery at 00:01 on 1/25/16. When he arrived, he found the leaking package turned on its side on the irregular belt by revenue recovery in front of door 220 with no one nearby. He used his decision tree to determine that the leaking package was hazardous and with an oxidizer label and a corrosive label. When Jeremy brought the package back to the dmp, he discovered that 1 of the 4 gallon jugs had a cracked cap and leaked out. It is quite possible that the person who unloaded the hazmat package onto the irreg. belt dropped it onto the belt with the arrows not facing up, causing the cap to crack.

column168: DRIVER WAS EN-ROUTE TO A DELIVERY AT THE POGO MINE WITH A TOTAL OF 49,000 LBS OF FREIGHT ON BOARD. AT MP 299 OF THE RICHARDSON HWY, THE DRIVER STATED HIS TRAILER TIRES WERE TRACKING OFF THE HIGHWAY IN THE SNOW AND IT PULLED HIS TRACTOR OFF THE ROADWAY AND THE ANGLE OF THE SHOULDER CAUSED THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO ROLL OVER. LOCAL NORTH STAR BOROUGH HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED WITH CLEAN-UP AND SALVAGE CREWS. 3 OF THE UN1789 IBC'S RUPTURED AND/OR LEAKED (1 COMPLETELY, 1 50%), UN1823 DRUMS WERE CRUSHED WITH ONE LEAKING ITS CONTENTS, AND THE UN2031 AND UN1797 IBC CLOSURES LEAKED ONTO THE SNOW, AND ICE COVERED GROUND. ONCE THE VEHICLES AND CONTAINERS WERE REMOVED FROM THE SCENE, ALL THE CONTAMINATED SNOW, ICE, AND DEBRIS WERE REMOVED AND SENT OFF-SITE TO BE NEUTRALIZED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF. A NEUTRALIZER FLUSH WAS THEN DONE AND COMPLETED OVER THE RELEASE AREA, THEN A LAYER OF CLEAN DIRT CAPPED THE RELEASE AREA PER THE APPROVED STATE OF ALASKA REMEDIATION PLAN. CONTINUED SOIL TESTING WILL BE CONDUCTED UNTIL SITE IS APPROVED FOR RESTORATION CLOSURE.
column169: FOR OPERATIONS, ON PREVENTION WE RE-ADDRESSED FOCUSING ON THE TASKS AT HAND WHICH WAS DRIVING. DO NOT BECOME DISTRACTED WHILE DRIVING.  REGARDING PACKAGING, IT IS MY OPINION THAT ONE-WAY OR DISPOSABLE N-R-IBC SHOULD NOT BE ALLOWED FOR TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL LIQUID PRODUCTS. THESE TYPES OF CONTAINERS CANNOT WITHSTAND MOST TRANSPORTATION ACCIDENTS.

A NEUTRALIZER FLUSH WAS THEN DONE AND COMPLETED OVER THE RELEASE AREA, THEN A LAYER OF CLEAN DIRT CAPPED THE RELEASE AREA PER THE APPROVED STATE OF ALASKA REMEDIATION PLAN. CONTINUED SOIL TESTING WILL BE CONDUCTED UNTIL SITE IS APPROVED FOR RESTORATION CLOSURE.

column168: WEARING PROPER PPE I RESPONDED TO A BOX THAT HAD LEAKED A LITTLE POWDER OUT THE SIDE. THE DECISION TREE AND MARKINGS ON THE OUTER BOX LED ME TO THE NON-FLAMMABLE GAS RESPONSE SHEET. I PLACED THE BOX AND CLEANED THE POWDER WITH A FIBER BROOM AND PLASTIC DUSTPAN AND BROUGHT THE BOX TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. AT THE DMP AREA I OPENED THE BOX TO FIND TWO SMALLER BOXES INSIDE. INSIDE THE SMALLER BOXES WERE KIDDIE FIRE EXTINGUISHERS. THE VALVE HAD OPENED. SO I TOOK OUT THE EXTINGUISHERS AND TOOK THE CYLINDERS TO PE FOR OUTSIDE PICK-UP. ALL THE POWDER IS LISTED IN THE NON-REGULATED CATEGORY LISTING. SO IT WAS DISPOSED OF IN THE TRASH.

On January 15, 2016 in East Chicago, Indiana a five (5) gallon plastic container of mercury debris waste was found to be tipped over inside at Tradebe Treatment and Recycling, LLC plant.  The trailer was being moved from Tradebe Transportation LLC Marport 10-day facility.  When the trailer was opened at the East Chicago facility the container was found to have tipped over and the lid was misaligned.    When the driver reached over and set the bucket up straight he noticed several balls of mercury were on the trailer floor.  After discovery, he reported the spillage and was instructed to prepare the trailer for the cleanup crew.  Tradebe personnel conducted the incident response and mercury recovery.   Inspection of the trailer floor and the material recovered indicates no releases from the trailer and that the small spill was confined to inside the trailer.  The Tradebe investigation indicates that the small container had fallen off a skid and onto the floor, jarring the lid off.  There is a question as to if the original shipper of the waste applied the lid correctly since Tradebe had not opened the container.
column169: Recommendations,    1. Driver is to ensure the manifest is signed and placed back in trailer when parked.    2. Driver is to ensure all containers are in the correct positions before signing and placing the manifest back in the trailer.

A shipment of hazardous waste was picked up by the driver and loaded onto his box truck.  The shipment was improperly packaged, outside in the rain, and overloaded for the container it was in.  Upon returning to the intermediate truck transfer facility, one of the cubic yard boxes had split down the side and several of the paint cans inside had leaked paint which was semi-hardened.  The liner of the cubic yard box was not compromised and nothing leaked outside the liner.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and overpacked the contents into a suitable salvage drum.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The shipment should never have been picked up in the condition it was presented.  The driver was issued a warning letter and retrained in proper container selection and pickup.

Norfolk Southern personnel reported an odor coming from tank car GATX28786.  Norfolk Southern sent SWS, an environmental emergency response contractor to inspect the car.  SWS reported upon inspection of GATX 28786, they found no evidence of a release.  Based on the inspection the information provided Norfolk Southern released the car for interchange to CSX.  This car was subsequently inspected on CSX property. By an FRA inspector and found to have a loose manway bolt.  The car was inspected again by CSX personnel and found to have a bad manway gasket.
column169: Norfolk Southern will provide more specific instruction to its contractor regarding proper inspection of rail cars.

column168: Tank Car GATX 26969 was reported leaking product in the rail yard.  The responder reported the leak source was at GATX 26969 manway fill hole. Upon further inspection, the manway fill hole swing bolts were found unsecured, allowing product to release when the car was moved.  The swing bolts were properly applied and secured mitigating any further release from GATX 26969.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column169: Spoke with shipper about incident and inspections of cars before leaving a facility, Shipper is going to send parts to qualified mobile tank car Repair Company and have PRD fixed.

column168: Responded to a leaking PKG on sort aisle, while wearing all appropriate PPE, upon locating leaking box, there was a very strong smell of acetone, box was also discolored in some areas, and only marking on outer box was ups label. Transported PKG back to clerk’s area, upon opening the box there was a ups labeled lab pack plastic envelope inside, sealed, upon opening it there was a 1 gallon jug of polish thinner inside, very strong odor, and wet residue in the bottom of the bag. Lid was slightly loose and a piece of plastic was in between lid and bottle, no other liquids in box. Contacted ups help desk, took photos as required, help desk said not to fully process pkg., so it was boxed and placed in a plastic bag. No MSDS could be found on this product, reference # given to me for this by help desk is 278927.
column169: TIGHTEN LID BEFORE SHIPPING AND HAVE CORRECT LABELING ON OUTER BOX.

column168: THE EMPLOYEE IN THE TRAILER AT DOOR 14 HAD JUST STARTED UNLOADING WHEN HE NOTICED A WET SPOT AROUND A HAZMAT PACKAGE. HE LEFT THE TRAILER   NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR. THE SUPERVISOR IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS. RESPONDED TO THE CALL. UTILIZED THE DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. BECAUSE THE PACKAGE WAS CORROSIVE, ALTERED PPE TO INCLUDE THE SILVER SHIELD INNER LINERS. TESTED THE PH OF THE LIQUID   FOUND IT TO BE APPROX 12. CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY. APPLIED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO THE LIQUID ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. STIRRED IT AROUND   THEN RETESTED THE PH. ONCE THE PH WAS IN THE NEUTRAL RANGE OF 6-9, ADDED CLAY ABSORBANT TO SOLIDIFY ANY REMAINING LIQUID. SWEPT UP ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS   PUT THEM INTO ANOTHER LINED SPILL TRAY. THEN TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHEN I OPENED THE BOX, I FOUND THAT 1 PLASTIC BOTTLE WAS CRACKED   ALL WERE SOILED BY THE PRODUCT.

AN UNLOADER WAS UNLOADING PACKAGES IN DOOR 20 WHEN HE NOTICED THAT THE A HAZMAT PACKAGE WAS LEAKING. HE LEFT THE TRAILER   TOLD THE NEAREST SUPERVISOR. SUPERVISOR IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS. RESPONDER UTILIZED DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY AND USED CLAY ABSORBANT TO SOLIDIFY ANY LIQUID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. SWEPT UP THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBANT   ADDED IT TO THE SPILL TRAY. THEN TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHEN THE BOX WAS OPENED, FOUND 6 METAL CANS HAD BEEN CRUSHED   DENTED AT THE BOTTOM   THAT ONE WAS LEAKING FROM THE DENTED AREA

column168: Driver was scheduled to unload 40,000 of Mineral Spirits NE to customer in Pueblo CO.    During the setup it was determined a non-compatible material was left in the tractor pump.    The pump was aired out during the customer's sampling process.    Driver failed to close pump properly, opened tanker, and released 229 GAL into customer's containment pit.   Pump was left open for approximately 1.5 minutes allowing material to gravity unload through open valves  Valve was closed and leak stopped.  All leaked material was contained in spill containment pits and cleaned out by outside environmental services company.  .
column169: Communicate incident to driver staff for training and communication.      Discuss with driver and administer discipline/training.      Conduct facility meeting, discuss the requirements around updating board, and how that contributed to this incident.      Administer new local policy that ALL pumps be double checked and flushed at Nexeo's facility PRIOR to leaving for deliveries.

column168: ED STAUB AND SON'S TRUCK #534 WAS HEADING WEST BOUND ON HWY 36 COMING DOWN FREDONYER MOUNTAIN. THE 2ND FORD RAGNER DRIVE BY A CLATRANS EMPLOYEE CAME INTO A DIRECT CONTRACT WITH THE FRONT OF TRUCK #534. TRUCK #534 CONTACTED THE SNOW BANK WITH ENOUGH FORCE TO DISCONNECT TANK FROM FRAME OF VEHICLE. TRUCK #534 CAME TO REST ON THE SHOULDER OF THE WEST BOUND LANE WITH THE TANK RESTING ON IT'S SIDE IN THE SNOW BANK. THERE WAS A SLOW DRIP OF FUEL COMING OUT OF THREE OF THE FOR DOME LIDS ON THE TANK. column168: A vehicle operated by Safety-Kleen Systems, Inc. was in route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the storage operation, it was discovered that approximately 24 ounces of material had escaped from a pinhole leak that had developed in the container. Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation and/or drop off, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Material Handlers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and has been asked to inspect all containers used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required specifications.

column168: On January 14, 2016, the Veolia driver was parked at the side of the highway (I37) to use a cell phone to contact his dispatcher.  A State Trooper saw him and stopped to make sure the driver was not having a problem.  During the conversation it was observed that the tank was sweating.  Upon further inspection, the leveler gauge on the cargo tank was discovered to be leaking - approximately one drip for every 3 minutes.  The driver contained the leak by hanging an empty 5 gallon bucket on the level indicator while the local Veolia office sent out an empty CTMV to which the load was then transferred.  The emptied CTMV that was leaking proceeded to the local Fleetpride service shop for repairs.
column169: Veolia drivers currently double check all gauges, valves and connections for leaks prior to transportation.  In the future, drivers will remain in attendance of the vehicle for a few extra minutes for observation to ensure no residual leaking occurs.

Approximately 35 gallons of UN1993 "Petrostep ES-65A" released from the 55 gallon poly drum due to a crack in the bottom of the drum due to damage caused by improper blocking and bracing for transport. All waste material was containerized for disposal.

column168: On January 28, 2016, at around 2:30 pm, a Tradebe Transportation (Tradebe) truck was returning to East Chicago, Indiana from a pick up in Minnesota via route I90/39/94 at approximately the 120 mile marker near Deforest Wisconsin when he was advised that of a potential release from the trailer by a truck driver following the Tradebe truck.  The driver immediately pulled over and evaluated the situation.   The driver observed drips coming from midpoint of the trailer on the passenger side.  The driver exited the busy highway and parked away from the highway on an asphalt surface.  The driver then placed a spill kit drum under the trailer where he observed drips seeping through the floor.  Next, the driver placed absorbent media around the recovery drum and under the trailer.  As an additional precaution, the driver set an absorbent boom under the trailer and along the edge of the asphalt pavement.  The driver applied absorbent inside the trailer between drums sitting on the trailer floor.  Tradebe office personnel notified the local agencies of the incident and then Tradebe personnel dispatched a private response contractor to conduct incident response.  The local agencies went to the site and conducted area surveillance.  The local agencies cleared the area and allowed the Tradebe contractor to perform the site response activities on the trailer and asphalt surface under the trailer.    The response contractor solidified the remaining material liquid in the metal drum; solidified the liquid in the spill collection drum with the absorbent swept up from the asphalt drive surface and then inspected the trailer to confirm success of their response activities.  Tradebe advised the state agency of the incident and response activities conducted by the contractor.   The drum in question was found to have a small tear in the rim seal at the base of the drum.
column169: Inspect all drums thoroughly before manifest is signed and the driver leaves the site.

On January 28, 2016, at 18:25 hours, a Transportation Manager at the CSXT Avon Terminal, in Avon, Indiana reported that a car inspector heard a hissing sound from atop of PROX 36686 a residue tank car of UN1075, Isobutane. The tank car was isolated and the shipper, Hollyfrontier Refining, was notified via Chemtrec, report #2016-0128-00262. Summit, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Avon Terminal. Summit found that the vapor valve was partially in the open position and both the vapor valve and "B" end liquid valve secondary closure plugs were not installed. The shipper representative, Mike Ernst Holly frontier Refining  214-356-3432, was notified of the situation found. Summit closed the vapor valve appropriately thus stopping the release. Both the vapor and liquid valve secondary closure plugs were properly secured and the tank car was released.    NARRI: 5x(4+5+0)x(2+0) = 90  Cause code:390

column168: The carrier's driver was unloading the CTMV when the two inch camlock fitting failed. The driver turned off the pump and closed the unloading line valves, which stopped the release. The package failure was determined to be caused by an unlined or coated stainless steel fitting which was incompatible with the lading. Two one-inch diameter holes were observed on the fitting collar. The fitting was replaced with a corrosive resistant plastic fitting. The duration of the release is estimated to have been 5-10 minutes. We dispatched an emergency response contractor to clean up the release. If an additional cause of the failure is determined which requires further investigation then upon receipt will provide a supplemental report.    Our reference: Event 49422

column168: On January 27, 2016, FRA inspector Kenneth Barefield discovered tank car GATX 28786 to have one of eight manway swing bolts less than tool tight.  On January 28, 2016, CSX hazardous materials employees responded to correct the exception for GATX 28786, a loaded tank car of Flammable Liquids, N.O.S. (turpentine crude sulfate) and discovered a vapor release from the manway.  The car was isolated and the shipper (Boise Paper); the NRC (report number 1139174); and the Florida State Watch Office (report number 1139174) were notified. CSX hazardous materials employees replaced the manway gasket and tightened all the manway bolts tool tight.  This incident did not require a special switching move or a 7.1.      Cause Code: 527  NARRI: 60

column62: Human Error; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: At 0900 hours on January 28, 2016, it was reported that railcar IAPX 1037, a load of Argon Refrigerated Liquid, was found venting improperly at the Kansas City Southern (KCS) Beaumont, TX yard.  The incident was reported to Chemtrec and the shipper was notified.    The shipper responded to secure the package. The KCS Environmental + Hazmat Department was updated by their responder and learned there were actually two points of release. The first point of release, and largest by volume, was a crack in the vaporizer coil. The vaporizer coil is located under the rail car, in between the two valve cabinets. The vaporizer is normally isolated without lading in the transportation mode. The release to the defective (cracked) vaporizer was caused by the Pressure Build Inlet Valve (V-3) being left in the open position by the offeror. Also, a second release was discovered from a loose valve packing on the Pressure Build Inlet Valve (V-3). The shipper responded to the incident and mitigated the release by closing the Pressure Build Inlet Valve and tightening the loose packing.      The crack in the vaporizer caused the package to be off specification and non-compliant per FRA. KCS Environmental + Hazmat spoke with FRA, Washington, DC, Kevin Blackwell and he authorized the movement of this off spec package back to origin in Nerderland, Texas, per 49CFR174.50, for repair or unloading before further transportation to home-shop under a One Time Movement Approval-3 secured by shipper.    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE TRAVELING, THE SAFE .TRANSPORTATION SERVICES, INC .VEHICLE ROLLED OVER, WHICH DAMAGED THE COMPARTMENT ON THE CARGO TANK TRAILER. ROMULUS FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE. TERRA CONTRACTING WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. THE CARGO TANK TRAILER CONTAINED 7,500 GALLONS OF GASOLINE. TERRA CONTRACTING RECOVERED APPROXIMATELY 6,000 GALLONS OF GASOLINE FROM THE DAMAGED TANKER INTO A RECOVERY TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 1,500 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WERE RELEASED TO THE ROADSIDE SOILS, AND ADJACENT DITCH. TERRA CONTRACTING PROCEEDED TO RECOVER THE FREE STANDING WATER AND IMPACTED SNOW FROM THE AFFECTED DITCH. ABSORBENT BOOM WAS APPLIED TO SECURE THE SITE. TERRA CONTRACTING RETURNED TO THE SITE TO EXCAVATE IMPACTED SOIL, PERFORM PERIODIC BOOM MAINTENANCE, AND RECOVER FREE LIQUIDS FROM THE IMPACTED AREAS, UNTIL NO FURTHER RESIDUALS REMAINED. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE.
column169: SAFE TRANSPORTATION SERVICES WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES AND DRIVER SAFETY TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: THE RELEASE OCCURRED AT A FACILITY LOADING DOCK AREA AS AN EMPLOYEE WAS ATTEMPTING TO OFFLOAD A PALLET OF STEEL 55 GALLON DRUMS (1A1) USING A POWERED FORKLIFT. UPON APPROACHING THE CONTAINERS, THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR INADVERTENTLY PUNCTURED ONE OF THE DRUMS WITH A FORKLIFT TINE. BECAUSE OF THE LOCATION AND SIZE OF THE PUNCTURE, NEAR THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM AND A FEW SQUARE INCHES, ALL OF THE CONTENTS WITH THE EXCEPTION OF A SMALL AMOUNT OF SLUDGE WERE RELEASED WITHIN A FEW SECONDS. PLANT PERSONNEL RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY TO CONTAIN AND COLLECT THE SPILLED LIQUID, AND ESTIMATE THAT "MOST" OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED. AT THE SAME TIME THE APPROPRIATE AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED. AS PART OF THE ENSUING RESPONSE ACTIVITIES AND AFTER COLLABORATION WITH THE MASSACHUSETTS DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION, THE CONCRETE SURFACE IMPACTED BY THE SPILL, AS WELL AS A LIMITED QUANTITY OF SOIL UNDERNEATH, WAS EXCAVATED AND RESTORED TO PREVIOUS CONDITIONS. THE EXCAVATED .MATERIALS WERE SENT OFFSITE FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.
column169: BEFORE BEING PERMITTED TO AGAIN A FORKLIFT, THE OPERATOR INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE EVENT WAS RETRAINED ON THE SAFE OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. THIS INCIDENT COULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED HAD THE OPERATOR HAD TAKEN MORE CARE IN HIS APPROACH AND HANDLING OF THE CONTAINERS.

column168: There was no tank, container, A Univar driver mistakenly took a load of sulfuric that was for NORTH LAKE ENERGY to COKEENERGY in East Chicago, IN.  NORTH LAKE and COKEENERGY share the same street address but different mail code locations.  The driver began to unload the sulfuric acid only to overflow the COKEENERGY tank and product has spilled on the ground.             Investigation recap:   •  Cokenergy and North Lake Energy share the same street address  • The driver had never been to North Lake Energy before, but had been to Cokenergy before  • As the Driver approached the delivery location, he made an assumption that Cokenergy had changed its name to Northlake.  • The driver went into the receiving trailer and gave his paperwork to the receiver. He went over the shipping papers (BOL  and the delivery form) and asked her if they had room for the load.  She signed off on both pieces of paperwork   • The driver did not verify or ask if the name of the company changed  • The driver parked next to tank at the unloading site and proceeded to prep for delivery by verifying the tank label, and checking out the safety shower.    • He then suited up into his PPE, hooked up the line, and proceeded to unload.   o Interviewing several other drivers that have been to this location, there is typically not a supervisor to witness or give additional approval to begin loading (other than the receiver that signs the paperwork).   • After 35-45 minutes of unloading, the tank started to overflow and the driver conducted an emergency shut down.  o  The shutdown was completed in ~20 seconds and over flow stopped in about 30 seconds.  • The driver then reported it to receiver.  o She called a supervisor to come out.  • Then a Supervisor came out and looked at the spill, told the driver that he was at the wrong location  and that SET (the emergency response team)was going to be coming out to clean it up.  • A couple of more guys came over and put caution tape around the tank and spill area.  • The driver then measured the amount of product left in the trailer and went into the receiver (Nancy) to correct the quantity delivered on the BOL, and let her know was ready to leave  • The driver then left and claimed he was not told not to leave which differs from the customer’s comments).
column169: • Driver will be retrained on verifying that he is at the correct customer  • Safety Stand down will be held with the Plain-field team reviewing the incident and importance of reading and following all paperwork  • Work with customer to create Bulk Site Profiles  • Work with customer with the ask the train their employees how to properly verify what the current level of product in the tank is (to prevent overflows

ON JANUARY 22, 2016 OUR DRIVER WAS HEADING NORTHBOUND ON INTERSTATE 85 IN HENDERSON, NORTH CAROLINA. THE WEATHER CONDITIONS WERE A MIXTURE OF SNOW AND SLEET AND DRIVING CONDITIONS, WERE BECOMING MORE HAZARDOUS. OUR DRIVER TOOK NOTICE OF THIS AND WAS IN THE PROCESS OF LOCATING A TRUCK STOP SO THAT HE COULD WAIT OUT THE WINTER STORM.     AS HE CONTINUED DRIVING NORTHBOUND HE HIT A PATCH OF SNOW AND ICE CAUSING THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO JACK KNIFE. THE 5TH WHEEL ON THE TRACTOR ABSORBED THE ENERGY OF THE JACK KNIFE AND CAUSED THE 5TH WHEEL PLATE TO SEPARATE FROM THE TRACTOR. AFTER THE SEPARATION OCCURRED THE TRAILER OVERTURNED BEFORE COMING TO A COMPLETE STOP IN THE NORTHBOUND LANES OF INTERSTATE 85.     AS THE TRAILER CAME TO A REST, BEING ON ITS SIDE, THE PRODUCT BEGAN TO LEAK FROM THE WASHOUT CAPS ON THE TRAILER. (THIS WAS A 4 COMPARTMENT TRAILER AND 3 OF THE 4 COMPARTMENTS WERE LOADED WITH PRODUCT.)    THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED BY THE RESPONDERS THAT WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE, AND EASTERN ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTRACTED TO HANDLE THE REMEDIATION OF THE SITE. THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT INTO ANY WATERWAY OR STORM DRAIN. THE MAJORITY OF THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED TO THE ACTUAL HIGHWAY, AND A SMALL PORTION MADE IT TO THE SHOULDER.     UPON CONDUCTING A POST-ACCIDENT INVESTIGATION AND ASSESSMENT OF THIS INCIDENT, IT HAS BEEN DETERMINED THAT THE CHEMICAL SPILL OCCURRED BECAUSE OF WORN OUT GASKETS IN THE WASHOUT CAPS. THE DRIVER FAILED TO FOLLOW COMPANY POLICY AND INSPECT THE GASKETS PRIOR TO LOADING IT WHICH IS A VIOLATION OF COMPANY POLICY.
column169: LANGER TRANSPORT HAS TERMINATED THE DRIVER THAT CAUSED THE SPILL FOR FAILING TO FOLLOW COMPANY POLICY IN REGARDS TO INSPECTING GASKETS THAT ARE INSIDE THE WASH OUT CAPS. column168: ON JANUARY 22, 2016 OUR DRIVER WAS HEADING NORTHBOUND ON INTERSTATE 85 IN HENDERSON, NORTH CAROLINA. THE WEATHER CONDITIONS WERE A MIXTURE OF SNOW AND SLEET AND DRIVING CONDITIONS, WERE BECOMING MORE HAZARDOUS. OUR DRIVER TOOK NOTICE OF THIS AND WAS IN THE PROCESS OF LOCATING A TRUCK STOP SO THAT HE COULD WAIT OUT THE WINTER STORM.     AS HE CONTINUED DRIVING NORTHBOUND HE HIT A PATCH OF SNOW AND ICE CAUSING THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO JACK KNIFE. THE 5TH WHEEL ON THE TRACTOR ABSORBED THE ENERGY OF THE JACK KNIFE AND CAUSED THE 5TH WHEEL PLATE TO SEPARATE FROM THE TRACTOR. AFTER THE SEPARATION OCCURRED THE TRAILER OVERTURNED BEFORE COMING TO A COMPLETE STOP IN THE NORTHBOUND LANES OF INTERSTATE 85.     AS THE TRAILER CAME TO A REST, BEING ON ITS SIDE, THE PRODUCT BEGAN TO LEAK FROM THE WASHOUT CAPS ON THE TRAILER. (THIS WAS A 4 COMPARTMENT TRAILER AND 3 OF THE 4 COMPARTMENTS WERE LOADED WITH PRODUCT.)    THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED BY THE RESPONDERS THAT WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE, AND EASTERN ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTRACTED TO HANDLE THE REMEDIATION OF THE SITE. THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT INTO ANY WATERWAY OR STORM DRAIN. THE MAJORITY OF THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED TO THE ACTUAL HIGHWAY, AND A SMALL PORTION MADE IT TO THE SHOULDER.     UPON CONDUCTING A POST-ACCIDENT INVESTIGATION AND ASSESSMENT OF THIS INCIDENT, IT HAS BEEN DETERMINED THAT THE CHEMICAL SPILL OCCURRED BECAUSE OF WORN OUT GASKETS IN THE WASHOUT CAPS. THE DRIVER FAILED TO FOLLOW COMPANY POLICY AND INSPECT THE GASKETS PRIOR TO LOADING IT WHICH IS A VIOLATION OF COMPANY POLICY.

column168: ON JANUARY 4, 2016, AT APPROXIMATELY 0720 HRS, HERCULES TRANSPORT, INC. WAS NOTIFIED THAT A PARKED BULK TRAILER APPEARED TO BE LEAKING A VAPOR. THE TRAILER IN QUESTION WAS PARKED AT A SECURE LOT LEASED BY THE COMPANY. THE TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH APPROXIMATELY 39,480 POUNDS OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. LOUISIANA STATE POLICE HOTLINE WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED (INCIDENT #16-00011). LSP AND LA DEQ RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. UPON INSPECTION, IT APPEARED THE SMALL LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE MANWAY COVER. UNDER SUPERVISION OF LSP AND DEQ, THE PRODUCT WAS OFFLOADED TO ANOTHER TRAILER. THE REMAINING PRODUCT LEFT IN THE TRAILER WAS SCRUBBED THROUGH WATER AND THE TRAILER ULTIMATELY FLARED DOWN. UPON REMOVING THE MANWAY COVER, IT APPEARED THE STEEL GASKET HAD A SMALL RAISED SPOT AT THE POINT WHERE THE PRODUCT HAD PASSED. IT IS OUR BELIEF THAT WHEN THE GASKET WAS INSTALLED BY A CONTRACTED PARTY, SOME FORM OF DEBRIS WAS TRAPPED BENEATH THE GASKET AND ULTIMATELY CAUSED THE FAILURE. THIS FORM IS SUBMITTED WITHOUT KNOWING THE EXACT AMOUNT OF RELEASE OR IF IT WAS ACTUALLY ABOVE THE REPORTABLE THRESHOLD. THE OFFLOADED TRAILER DELIVERED 39,320 POUNDS OF THE ORIGINAL 39,480. AN APPROXIMATE AMOUNT UNACCOUNTED FOR WAS 31 GALLONS. THE MAJORITY OF THIS AMOUNT MAY HAVE BEEN SCRUBBED THROUGH WATER AND FLARED OFF. THERE WERE NO INJURIES, ROAD CLOSURE, OR EVACUATIONS AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.
column169: THE GASKET IN QUESTION WAS INSTALLED BY A CONTRACTED PARTY PERFORMING THE 5 YEAR INSPECTION. A COMPLETE CHECK OF ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS ON THE TRAILER WAS CONDUCTED AND A NEW GASKET INSTALLED.

column168: ASOX 296026    ASOX 296026 WAS DISCOVERED IN ROUTE UP-COLTN-BNSF TO BE LEAKING VAPOR FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAR HAD FAILED DUE TO A DEFECTIVE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE.  UNITED PUMPING SERVICE (UPS) WAS CONTRACTED TO ASSIST WITH THE REPAIR. THE VALVE WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH A PLUG.        CTCX733272    IT APPEARS THAT THE BOV FLANGE HAD LOOSENED DURING TRANSPORT. IT WAS OBSERVED BY THE UPRR HAZMAT RESPONSE MANAGER ON SITE THAT A VERY SMALL RELEASE OF PRODUCT OCCURRED AT THE RATE OF ONE (1) SMALL DRIP PER TWO (2) MINUTES. UPRR USED A SINGLE SPILL PAD WITH A SHEET OF PLASTIC AND SOME DUCT TAPE WRAPPED AROUND THE BOV TO CONTAIN THE DRIP. THE UPRR HAZMAT RESPONDER INITIALLY THOUGHT THERE WAS AN ISSUE WITH A VACUUM RELIEF VALVE ON TOP OF THE CAR DUE TO A SECOND LEAKING CAR CONNECTED TO THIS CAR. AFTER FURTHER INSPECTION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS NOT A SAFETY VALVE VRV ISSUE, BUT SOME MINOR EMISSION WAS BEING DETECTED IN THE FLANGE AREA OF THE CTCX733272 CAR. THE HAZMAT MANAGER ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE BOV FLANGE BOLT, AND CALLED TO INFORM THAT THE FLANGE HAD STARTED TO DRIP, AT A DROP FOR EVERY TWO MINUTES. AT THIS POINT HE DECIDED WE NEEDED TO CALL OUT A RESPONSE TO COMPLETE A TRANS LOADING OF THE RAILCAR.
column169: ASOX 296026    AMERICA STYRENICS COMPANY HAS DECIDED TO LOOK AT OUR HM201 TIMING WITHIN THE HM216B PROCESS TO IDENTIFY A MORE STRINGENT QUALIFICATIONS PROCESS FROM THE SHOPS. THIS PROGRAM WILL HELP AMERICA STYRENICS IDENTIFY TIMING FROM PREVIOUS FAILURES TO HELP SET UP A MORE EFFICIENT TQ PROGRAM TO ELIMINATE THESE TYPES OF FAILURES.       CTCX733272    AMERICAN STYRENICS COMPANY HAS DECIDED TO LOOK AT OUR HM201 TIMING WITHIN THE HM216B PROCESS TO IDENTIFY A MORE STRINGENT QUALIFICATION PROCESS FROM THE SHOPS. THIS CAR WAS ONLY ITS 4TH CYCLE SINCE COMING INTO SERVICE FROM THE MANUFACTURER, AND WE FEEL THIS IS MUCH TOO SOON TO BEGIN SEEING ANY ISSUE WITH GASKET, O-RING FAILURE. SO WE WILL CONDUCT AN AUDIT OF OTHER CARS THAT WENT INTO SERVICE AROUND THE SAME PERIOD TO CHECK IF THIS IS AN ISOLATED INCIDENT TO HELP PREVENT THIS TYPE OF LEAK FROM OCCURRING IN THE FUTURE.

column168: DRIVER WAS MAKING A LEFT TURN TO ENTER RAMP TO INTERSTATE 10 AT AN UNSAFE SPEED. THE EXCESS SPEED CAUSED A SHIFT IN THE LIQUID CARGO THAT RESULTED IN THE VEHICLE ROLLING ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE. THE POLICE WERE ON THE SCENE SHORTLY AFTER THE CRASH OCCURRED. EMERGENCY RESPONDERS WERE CONTACTED AND ARRIVED ON THE SCENE WITHIN A COUPLE OF HOURS. AFTER EVALUATING THE SCENE, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING. THE LEAK WAS APPARENTLY COMING FROM THE VAPOR RECOVERY LINE ON THE TOP OF THE TANK NEAR THE DOME LID. THE LEAK COULD NOT BE STOPPED. THE PRODUCT WAS TRANS LOADED INTO A CLEAN TANK TRUCK THAT WAS BROUGHT TO THE SCENE. THIS PROCESS DID NOT BEGIN UNTIL SEVERAL HOURS AFTER THE CRASH. THE PRODUCT WAS BROUGHT BACK TO THE SHIPPER WHERE IT WAS DETERMINED THAT 204 GALLONS WERE LOST FROM THE ORIGINAL SHIPMENT.

column169: THIS WAS NOT THE FAULT OF THE DRIVER OR THE TANKER. EVERY SAFETY MEASURE WAS IN PLACE AND WORKED WELL.     THIS INCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY THE OTHER DRIVER WHO WAS CITED.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 8:45 AM, THE DRIVER WAS PROCEEDING ONTO THE I-275 WB ON-RAMP FROM I-75 NB. THE DRIVER WAS PROCEEDING TO HIS FIRST DELIVERY OF THE DAY, AND HAD 886 GALLONS OF #2 DYED DIESEL REMAINING ONBOARD. THE CONDITIONS ON THE GROUND WERE CLEAR; THERE HAD BEEN A SNOWFALL RECENTLY, HOWEVER THE ROADWAY UPON WHICH THE DRIVER WAS PROCEEDING WAS DRY.     AS THE DRIVER PROCEEDED THROUGH THE LONG CURVE OF THE ON-RAMP, HE STATED THAT HE HEARD A LOUD MECHANICAL NOISE WHILE SITTING IN THE CAB OF HIS UNIT BEFORE THE UNIT SUDDENLY VEERED TO THE LEFT. THE UNIT IMMEDIATELY STRUCK THE GUARD RAIL ON THE DRIVER’S SIDE. THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO CORRECT, BUT THE UNIT STRUCK A SECTION OF THE GUARD RAIL AND FLIPPED THE UNIT. AS THE UNIT BEGAN ITS FIRST ROLL, THE REMAINS OF THE GUARD RAIL SECTION AFFECTED HOOKED ONTO THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE CAB AND RIPPED THE DOOR FROM THE CAB’S FRAME. THE UNIT LANDED UPSIDE DOWN, NOSE FIRST INTO THE ROADWAY AND WAS PROPELLED FORWARD BEFORE IT CAME TO A REST ON THE DRIVER’S SIDE. THE LINES LEADING DIRECTLY FROM THE BARREL TO THE LOAD HEADS WERE DAMAGED AND AN ESTIMATED EIGHT GALLONS OF PRODUCT LEAKED OUT. THE BARREL SEALS WERE ALSO COMPROMISED ON TOP OF THE UNIT. HOWEVER THE INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT LESS THAN A QUARTER GALLON ESCAPED BEFORE THE UNIT WAS RIGHTED.     THE LOCAL POLICE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED WITHIN TEN MINUTES. HOWEVER, THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN FROM THE SCENE BY AMBULANCE, AND COMPANY REPRESENTATIVES WERE NOT CONTACTED UNTIL AFTER THE UNIT HAD BEEN RIGHTED, APPROXIMATELY ONE HOUR LATER. THE UNIT WAS TOWED FROM THE SCENE TO A LOCAL TOW YARD. THE INITIAL REPORT TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND THE OHIO EPA OFFICE WERE ERRONEOUS; MORE THAN THIRTY GALLONS WERE INITIALLY BELIEVED TO HAVE LEAKED OUT. DURING THE COMPANY’S INVESTIGATION, THE INVENTORY TAKEN FROM WHAT WAS PUMPED OFF OF THE AFFECTED UNIT COMPARED TO WHAT HAD BEEN ONBOARD FROM THE PREVIOUS EVENING REVEALED A DISCREPANCY OF ONLY EIGHT (8) GALLONS. HOWEVER, THE COMPANY BROUGHT IN ENVIRONMENTAL ENTERPRISES, INC. TO CLEAR THE ROADWAY OF RESIDUAL PRODUCT. THE REMAINING 878 GALLONS WERE RECOVERED FROM THE UNIT.
column169: LYKINS OIL COMPANY REVIEWS ALL INCIDENTS TO DETERMINE WHETHER OR NOT SUCH INCIDENTS COULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED OR OTHERWISE PREVENTED. AS OF THIS WRITING, LYKINS OIL COMPANY HAS YET TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT. WE HAVE DONE A REVIEW OF THE EMPLOYEE’S PERFORMANCE, AND TAKEN INTO CONSIDERATION HIS TENURE WITH THE COMPANY. WE DO NOT FEEL THAT THIS EMPLOYEE WAS AT-FAULT FOR THIS INCIDENT; HOWEVER WE ARE CONTINUING OUR INVESTIGATION INTO THIS ACCIDENT AND THE SUBSEQUENT LOSS OF THE UNIT INVOLVED.     DURING OUR NEXT QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETING, OUR DRIVERS WILL BE BRIEFED ON THE INCIDENT, AS WELL AS THE CONSEQUENCES OF THE EMPLOYEE’S ACTIONS. THE DRIVERS WILL BE REMINDED TO DRIVE SAFELY IN SUCH CONDITIONS, ESPECIALLY TO GIVE THEMSELVES ENOUGH REACTION TIME TO AVOID ANY OTHER COLLISIONS OR OTHER CHANGES IN CIRCUMSTANCES WHILE DRIVING ON THE ROADWAYS. THE VEHICULAR MAINTENANCE DEPARTMENT HAS ALSO BEEN REMINDED TO REGULARLY

column168: WHILE DRIVING ON THE MILL ROAD OVERPASS OF US ROUTE 1, THE FRONT PASSENGER SIDE TIRE CAME INTO CONTACT WITH THE SNOW PILED INTO THE SHOULDER OF THE HIGHWAY. THIS JERKED THE TRUCK AND THE DRIVER TURNED THE STEERING WHEEL TO CORRECT THE ISSUE. WHEN THE TRUCK CLEARED THE SNOW, THE MOMENTUM STARTED A SWERVE TOWARDS THE TRUCK'S DRIVER'S SIDE, RESULTING IN A ROLL-OVER. EMERGENCY RESPONSE NOTIFICATION WERE MADE IMMEDIATELY, AND THE COMPANY'S SENIOR LEADERSHIP TEAM MET TO DISCUSS AND TAKE DECISIVE ACTION ON GETTING THE TRUCK RIGHTED AND BROUGHT TO A SAFE FACILITY TO BEGIN THE REMOVAL OF PROPANE FROM THE CARGO TANK. THIS PROCESS WAS AIDED BY THE PRESENCE OF ONE OF THE COMPANY'S INTERNAL PROPANE MATERIAL EXPERTS.     THE RELEASE OF PROPANE WAS LIMITED TO THE CONTENTS OF THE DELIVERY LINE AND THE ADJACENT PIPING (ESTIMATED AT 7 GALLONS), WHICH VAPORIZED DUE TO THE BREACH OF THE HOSE AND CRACK IN THE PIPING. THIS RELEASE TOOK THE FORM OF VAPORIZED PRODUCT, WHICH QUICKLY DISSIPATED INTO THE AIR. GIVEN THE OPEN AIR NATURE OF THE INCIDENT, THE MATERIAL DID NOT PRESENT A THREAT TO THE HEALTH OR WELL BEING OF ANYONE IN THE AREA, AND COULD NOT BE COLLECTED.
column169: THE COMPANY HAS RELEASED AN EVENT FLASH REGARDING THE INCIDENT TO ALL DRIVERS, INFORMING THEM OF THE RISK ASSOCIATED WITH DRIVING IN CONDITIONS WITH ACCUMULATED SNOW. FURTHER, ANNUAL TRAINING PERTAINING TO ROLLOVER PREVENTION WILL BE UPDATED WITH INFORMATION REGARDING THIS EVENT TO INCREASE DRIVER UNDERSTANDING OF AVOIDANCE OF SIMILAR INCIDENTS.

column168: ON JANUARY 21, 2016 OUR TRUCK AND END DUMP TRAILER ARRIVED AT GERDAU MAC STEEL IN FT SMITH AR TO PICK UP A LOAD AT APPROXIMATELY 13:00 HRS. THE EQUIPMENT WAS INSPECTED BY THE DRIVER PRIOR TO LOADING WITH NO PROBLEMS FOUND. THE TRAILER WAS LOADED AT THE FACILITY WITH 33,400 POUNDS OF PRODUCT. AFTER LOADING WAS COMPLETE THE DRIVER CHARGED THE TRAILER AIR SYSTEM AND BEGAN MOVING THE TRUCK OUT OF THE LOADING AREA TO A TARPING AREA APPROXIMATELY 200 YARDS FROM THE LOADING AREA. WHEN THE TRUCK ARRIVED AT THE TARPING AREA THE DRIVER SET THE PARKING BRAKE IN PREPARATION TO LEAVE THE CAB TO TARP THE LOAD. THE DRIVER NOTICED IN HIS MIRROR MATERIAL RUNNING OUT THE BACK OF THE END DUMP. THE DRIVER THEN RELEASED THE TRAILER CHARGE AIR VALVE WHICH CLOSED THE TAILGATE AND STOPPED THE RELEASE. APPROXIMATELY 10,00 LBS OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A DEFECTIVE VALVE ON THE AUTOMATIC TAILGATE RELEASE SYSTEM, WHICH UNLATCHED THE TAILGATE WHEN THE TRAILER AIR SYSTEM WAS CHARGED BY THE DRIVER.     THE DRIVER THEN CALLED HIS DISPATCHER TO REPORT THE SPILL. BECAUSE WE WERE STILL AT THE SHIPPER, MAC STEEL CALLED CLEAN HARBORS AT APPROXIMATELY 14:52, AND A REMEDIATION CREW WAS DISPATCHED FOR TULSA OK FOR CLEANUP. THE CLEANUP CREW ARRIVED AT 18:30 TO BEGIN CLEANUP. CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED AT 22:00
column169: OUR TRAILERS ARE EQUIPPED WITH SQUEEZE BOLTS THAT POSITIVELY HOLDS THE REAR GATE CLOSED. WE HAD CHANGED OUR POLICY TO MAKE SURE THESE BOLTS ARE ENGAGED BEFORE THE TRAILER IS LOADED. THIS WILL PREVENT SPILLS IF EVER WE HAVE A PROBLEM WITH THE AUTOMATIC RELEASE SYSTEM AGAIN.

column168: WHILE THE LOADED GASOLINE TANKER WAS CLIMBING A SLIGHT INCLINE GRADE AT A SLOWER SPEED ON I-90, A PASSENGER VEHICLE TRAVELING AT A HIGHER SPEED LOST CONTROL ON THE ICY ROAD AND SLAMMED INTO THE TANKER AND PUSHING THE TANKER INTO THE SNOW BANK WHICH CAUSED THE TANKER TO LEAVE THE ROADWAY. THE PUP TANKER CAME TO REST ON ITS SIDE TO AN APPROXIMATE 85 DEGREE ROLLOVER. THE PPV (POSITIVE PRESSURE VACUUM) VENT LOCATED INTERNALLY ON THE TOP OF THE TANKER WAS DISCOVERED TO BE IN AN OPEN POSITION, AND AS IT WAS BELOW THE GASOLINE LEVEL IN THE TANKER, IT LEAKED GASOLINE. IT WASN'T A GUSHING LEAK, MORE LIKE JUST A TRICKLE. BEING SUBMERGED, IT IS NOT POSSIBLE TO MANUALLY CLOSE THE VENT. SAND WAS PUT DOWN ON THE ROADWAY WHICH WAS SLOPED DOWN AND AWAY FROM AN WATER BODIES. THE SAND CAUGHT MOST OF THE FUEL AND FINALLY AN NRC ENGINEER PUT A 40 GALLON CAN UNDER THE LEAKING VENT. THE CLEANUP AND UNLOADING OF THE TANKER TOOK ABOUT 8 HOURS. SOIL SAMPLES WERE TAKEN BY WASHINGTON STATE DEPARTMENT OF ECOLOGY IN THE AREA AND NO FURTHER REMEDIATION IS REQUIRED.
column169: WE ARE CHANGING OUR MAINTENANCE POLICY ON THIS PARTICULAR STYLE OF VENT. IT IS OUR UNDERSTANDING THAT THESE VENTS ARE ONLY REPLACED WHEN THEY FAIL DURING ANNUAL TESTING PERFORMED BY A CERTIFIED TESTING FIRM. WE ARE GOING TO REPLACED THESE VENTS EVERY TWO YEARS REGARDLESS OF IF THEY PASS THE ANNUAL PRESSURE AND VACUUM TEST. SINCE THE VENT PASSED THE ANNUAL TEST IN MAY 2015 THEN LEAKED 8 MONTHS LATER AT 4 YEARS OF AGE, WE BELIEVE BIANNUAL REPLACEMENT OF THE VENT WILL IMPROVED THE LIKELIHOOD OF THE VENT PREFORMING CORRECTLY. THERE ARE AS MANY AS 6 OF THESE VENTS ON EACH TANKER UNIT. AT THIS TIME THESE VENTS COST $55 EACH. AS WE STUDY THE DOME LID WHERE THIS VENT IS MOUNTED, IT IS POSSIBLE IN THE SAME KIND OF OCCURRENCE, TO SEAL THE VENT PORT WITH A THIN PIECE OF WOOD PLANK. IF THE SITUATION WAS A 180 DEGREE ROLLOVER IT WOULD BE IMPOSSIBLE TO ACCESS THE VENT PORT. WE NEVER WANT TO EXPERIENCE A ROLLOVER, AND THIS IS THE ONLY ONE IN THE LAST 20 YEARS. SAFETY IS OUR TOP PRIORITY AND WE STRIVE TO HAVE SAFE INCIDENT FREE VOYAGES.

column168: DRIVER WAS LOADING OUR TRANSPORT AT MARATHONS NORTH MUSKEGON TERMINAL. WHEN LOADING, HE ATTACHED THE LOADING ARM OF THE LOADING RACK TO THE NUMBER 2 COMPARTMENT ON OUR TRANSPORT. HE PUNCHED IN 4000 GALLONS INTO THE COMPUTER FOR LOADING WHICH WAS A MISTAKE, OUR COMPARTMENT # 2 ONLY HOLDS 2000 GALLONS. WHEN THE FUEL GOT TO THE TOP OF THE COMPARTMENT AND HIT THE OVERFILL PROBE, IT SHOULD HAVE SHUT THE LOADING RACK WITH THE DRIVER WAS USING DOWN, IT DID NOT, AND WHEN THE TANK GOT FULL AND STARTED TO OVERFILLING IT TOOK THE DRIVER 10-20 SECONDS TO SHUT THE RACK DOWN. THE ESTIMATED 200 GALLONS THAT WAS SPILLED WAS CONTAINED AT THE TERMINALS LOADING RACK AND CLEANED UP BY IN HOUSE WORKERS AND OUR DRIVER. THEY ALLOWED THE DRIVER TO FINISH FILLING THE COMPARTMENTS HE HAD LEFT UNDER SUPERVISION. WE WERE THEN INSTRUCTED THAT WE NEEDED TO HAVE OUR TRAILERS OVERFILL SCULLY SYSTEM INSPECTED AND CHECKED OUT BEFORE WE COULD USE IT AGAIN AT THE TERMINAL. WE TOOK THE TRAILER TO ST. JOHN TUCK AND TRAILER REPAIR TO HAVE THE SCULLY OVERFILL SYSTEM INSPECTED AND REPAIRED. THEY DISCOVERED 3 WEAK PROBES THAT THEY REPLACED AND SOME CORROSION DAMAGE TO SOME OF THE COMPUTER BOARDS THAT ARE THE MAIN BRAIN FOR THE OVERFILL SYSTEM. THEY ALSO FOUND A SPOT THAT HAD BEEN PREVIOUSLY WORKED ON, AND HAD BEEN WIRED WRONG WHICH MIGHT HAVE CONTRIBUTED WITH THE SYSTEM SHOWING, AND GETTING GREEN LIGHT THE TERMINAL WHEN IT SHOULDN'T HAVE. WE BASICALLY ENDED UP REPLACING THE WHOLE SCULLY SYSTEM WITH AN UPDATED ONE. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS REGARDING THIS THEN PLEASE FEEL FREE TO CONTACT ME.
column169: WE HAD A DRIVERS MEETING TO STRESS THE IMPORTANCE OF IT BEING THEIR RESPONSIBILITY TO MAKE SURE THAT THEY'RE PUTTING THE RIGHT INFORMATION, AND USING THE CORRECT LOADING ARMS AND MAKING SURE THAT THEY ARE ATTACHED TO THE RIGHT COMPARTMENTS WHEN GOING THROUGH A FILL, IN CASE THE OVERFILL SYSTEM FAILS. WE ALSO LIMITED THE COMPANY'S THAT CAN WORK ON THE OVERFILL SYSTEM ON OUR TRANSPORT TRAILERS. WE ARE ONLY ALLOWING 2 REPAIR FACILITIES THAT ARE AUTHORIZED DEALERS OF THE TYPE OF OVERFILL SYSTEMS WE USE ON OUR TRAILERS TO DO SERVICE WORK ON THEM. WE ARE ALSO HAVING THESE COMPANIES DO AN ANNUAL INSPECTION AND TEST THE SYSTEM ONCE A YEAR. ONCE AGAIN, IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS WITH THIS INFORMATION PLEASE FEEL FREE TO CONTACT ME.     DENNIS J DERRER,  DERRER OIL CO. II

column168: DISCIPLINE 0722 ON THE MORNING OF THE 9TH OF JANUARY, A KEY OIL (KO) TRANSPORT VEHICLE WAS INVOLVED IN A ONE VEHICLE ROLLOVER ACCIDENT AT CLARKSVILLE PARK AND WEST TRINITY LANE IN NASHVILLE TN. THE KO TRUCK WAS HEADED EAST TO THE INTERSECTION OF CLARKSVILLE PARK TO A RED LIGHT. HE APPLIED A FIRM BRAKE TO STOP, JUST BEFORE THE LIGHT TURNED GREEN AND THE DRIVER PROCEEDED. HIS LOAD SURGED FORWARD AS A RESULT TO APPLIED BRAKES AND AS HE MADE A HARD LEFT TURN (ON AN UP GRADE) THE CENTER OF GRAVITY OF HIS LOAD PUSHED THE TRUCK OVER ON TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRUCK IN THE FAR RIGHT LANE OF CLARKVILLE PIKE HEADING NORTHBOUND.     METRO DAVIDSON COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT, WEST NASHVILLE TOWING, AND THE METRO POLICE ALL RESPONDED. 45 BAGS OF OIL DRY, 15 BOOMS, 10 PADS AND 70 CANS OF FIRE AID FOAM WAS USED TO MITIGATE THE RELEASE.
column169: THE DRIVER RECEIVED TRAINING AND DISCIPLINE, 5 DAY SUSPENSION, A DAY OF REMEDIAL DEFENSIVE DRIVER TRAINING. A ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS ON WHAT CAUSED THE SURGE IN HIS LOAD AND HOW TO SUPPRESS IT. THEN HE SPENT A 2 WEEKS WITH A BEHIND WHEEL INSTRUCTOR, TO SEE OTHER WAYS TO IMPROVE HIS PROCEDURES, DRIVING TECHNIQUE AND ALTERNATE ROUTES TO AVOID THAT INTERSECTION.

column168: DRIVER MADE HEATING OIL DELIVERY TO WRONG ADDRESS/
column169: THERE ARE ALREADY CODES AND STANDARDS IN PLACE, STATING THAT THE FILL, VENT AND ALL PIPING MUST BE REMOVED WHEN THE TANK IS REMOVED (NFPA 31 SEC. 7.13.1) THAT NO ONE SEEMS TO PAY ATTENTION TO THAT WOULD PREVENT THIS TYPE OF ERROR. DRIVER MADE DELIVERY TO WRONG HOUSE. THERE WAS NO OIL TANK IN HOUSE BUT OIL FILL WAS STILL IN PLACE OUTSIDE. OUR DRIVER'S ARE TRAINED NOT TO MAKE DELIVERY WITHOUT A WORKING VENT ALARM, WHICH IN THIS CASE HE COULD NOT HAVE HAD. DRIVER WAS TERMINATED AFTER THIS INCIDENT.
